(337, 1, '2013-01-12 21:19:57', '2013-01-12 09:19:57', '<div class="gallery"><a class="fancybox" title="Comments made on facebook would appear on live TV." href="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1.jpg" rel="gallery1"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-338 " alt="Ulive comments page" src="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen1-200x200.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a><a class="fancybox" title="Facebook users could vote in polls which would be discussed by the presenters" href="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2.jpg" rel="gallery1"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-339 " alt="Ulive voting page " src="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen2-200x200.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a><a class="fancybox" title="Facebook users could stream Ulive from within the app" href="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3.jpg" rel="gallery1"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-340 " alt="Ulive streaming page" src="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen3-200x200.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a><a class="fancybox" title="Users could invite their friends to take part in the discussions" href="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4.jpg" rel="gallery1"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-341 " alt="Ulive invite page" src="http://localhost/techblog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/ulive-screen4-200x200.jpg" width="200" height="200" /></a></div>\r\n<h3>Goals</h3>\r\nThis project aimed to create a Facebook app housed on the TVNZU page which allowed facebook users to watch the live show. It was to allow the users to get involved in the discussions the presenters were having and even get their comments to appear in real time on live TV. It was also to create a sense of community within the users friends by allowing them to invite their friends to watch the show and also display a list of which of your friends were currently tuned in via the app.\r\n<h3>Technology</h3>\r\nThis project was built on the Zend Framework and implements the Facebook API, JQuery, AJAX, a custom scroll bar JS library and of course HTML &amp; CSS.\r\n<h3>Challenges</h3>\r\nThe main challenge was that discussion feed needed to have the same user experience as Facebook but the feed functionality isn''t part of the Facebook API and it needed to poll the server to add new comments without refreshing. The app also had to integrate with the users friends list and keep a track of who was online so we could display if any of your friends were watching and also have an invite mechanic. There was also the archiving of old discussions and polls as well as the feed moderation for the comments that went to air and CMS for the app.\r\n<h3>Solutions</h3>\r\nWe had to recreate the Facebook feed''s functionality from scratch with the added ability to flag posts for moderator review. This became a very difficult task when there''s so much integration. Every time we AJAX''d in a new set of posts we had to bump the same number off the bottom so the pagination was intact while keeping their indexes for the likes and times all correct. We had to update the posts times, amount of likes and comment totals and then once everything was loaded, refresh the custom scroll bar height. The scroll lock button paused new comments from auto-updating which was also quite difficult to get working seamlessly.\r\n\r\nConnecting people with their friends was an important part of the app. We kept a database record of the Facebook ID''s of everyone who logged into the app against a timestamp and if you''d polled our server in the last 30 seconds we considered you to be in current use of the app. We then would look at the logged in users friends list and cross section that with the people who are currently logged in and display their profile picture and a link to their profile in a grid under the X Friends Watching heading. From here you could also invite your friends to watch the show through the Ulive app and this was done with the Facebook API''s App Invite functionality.\r\n\r\nThe CMS was relatively straight forward, once a comment was approved to go to air it would be sent via a CURL request to an API at the TVNZ studio. This would then run through their system and be put up on the screen along with the users Name, Profile pic and Age which we got from their Facebook profile.\r\n<h3>Results</h3>\r\nThis project turned out to be a great piece of programming. The integration of so many technologies ended up seeming pretty smooth despite having to do a lot of bug fixing and tying up loose ends. Integrating a Facebook app with a live TV show was a first for me and actually a world wide first which caught the attention of a lot of people in technology sphere.\r\n<h3>Recognition</h3>\r\nThis app was featured on the Facebook developer blog and was also featured on quite a few online newspapers and blogs.\r\n<h3>Additional</h3>\r\nThe site has undergone a design overhaul since we launched it back in 2010 but its still up and running: <a title="Ulive facebook app" href="https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/" target="_blank">https://apps.facebook.com/tvnz-ulive/</a>', 'Ulive', 'This project encompassed a wide range of web technologies. It was the first facebook app to allow users to interact with live television and was featured on facebook''s developer blog.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ulive', '', '', '2013-01-13 22:12:35', '2013-01-13 10:12:35', '', 6, 'http://localhost/techblog/?page_id=337', 0, 'page', '', 0),
